Over the house itself , he exercised the same imaginary power as over its inhabitants and their affairs . 
Assuredly , this stall of Silas Wegg's was the hardest little stall of all the sterile little stalls in London . 
It gave you the face ache to look at his apples , the stomach ache to look at his oranges , the tooth ache to look at his nuts . 
Whether from too much east wind or no it was an easterly corner the stall , the stock , and the keeper , were all as dry as the Desert . 
Wegg was a knotty man , and a close grained , with a face carved out of very hard material , that had just as much play of expression as a watchman's rattle . 
When he laughed , certain jerks occurred in it , and the rattle sprung . 
Mr Wegg was an observant person , or , as he himself said , 'took a powerful sight of notice' . 
