It was the queerest of rooms , fitted and furnished more like a luxurious amateur tap room than anything else within the ken of Silas Wegg . 
There were two wooden settles by the fire , one on either side of it , with a corresponding table before each . 
On the hob , a kettle steamed on the hearth , a cat reposed . 
Facing the fire between the settles , a sofa , a footstool , and a little table , formed a centrepiece devoted to Mrs Boffin . 
They were garish in taste and colour , but were expensive articles of drawing room furniture that had a very odd look beside the settles and the flaring gaslight pendent from the ceiling . 
