This dignitary , conferring in secrecy with John Rokesmith on the subject of punch and wines , bent his head as though stooping to the Papistical practice of receiving auricular confession . 
Likewise , on John's offering a suggestion which didn't meet his views , his face became overcast and reproachful , as enjoining penance . 
The best of it was , that Bella and John and the cherub had made a covenant that they would not reveal to mortal eyes any appearance whatever of being a wedding party . 
Now , the supervising dignitary , the Archbishop of Greenwich , knew this as well as if he had performed the nuptial ceremony . 
